  "prompt": "Why doesn't the Media Player Classic produce sound and how can it be fixed?",
  "response": "There are several potential reasons why Media Player Classic might not produce sound, and here are some troubleshooting steps:\n\n1. Audio Codec Issues\n- Ensure you have the proper audio codecs installed\n- Download and install K-Lite Codec Pack or VLC codec pack\n- Update existing codecs\n\n2. Sound Settings\n- Check Windows sound settings\n- Verify volume is not muted\n- Confirm correct audio output device is selected\n- Test sound in other media players\n\n3. Audio Configuration in Media Player Classic\n- Open audio settings in the player\n- Select correct audio output device\n- Check audio renderer settings\n- Verify audio filters are configured correctly\n\n4. System Audio Troubleshooting\n- Restart audio services\n- Update or reinstall sound card drivers\n- Check Windows sound settings\n- Run Windows audio troubleshooter\n\n5. Software-Specific Solutions\n- Update Media Player Classic to latest version\n- Reinstall the media player\n- Check for known software conflicts\n\n6. Advanced Fixes\n- Run MPC as administrator\n- Reset player configuration\n- Disable hardware acceleration temporarily\n\nIf these steps don't resolve the issue, you might need to perform more advanced troubleshooting or consider using an alternative media player.",
